+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0119CwoCjguAKJkj4oq8Z5LN","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Task Queue System\n     2→\n     3→Build a fully-featured in-memory task queue system from scratch. The system should grow incrementally through 12 phases, each introducing new capabilities that build on the foundation laid by earlier phases.\n     4→\n     5→## Overview\n     6→\n     7→Your task queue should support adding tasks, processing them, and managing their lifecycle. Think of it like a simplified version of systems like Bull, BeeQueue, or Celery -- but entirely in-memory with no external dependencies.\n     8→\n     9→The system evolves through 12 phases of increasing sophistication:\n    10→\n    11→1. **Basic queue** -- adding and processing tasks in order\n    12→2. **Named queues** -- multiple independent queues\n    13→3. **Priority** -- some tasks are more urgent than others\n    14→4. **Delayed tasks** -- tasks that should wait before becoming available\n    15→5. **Retry with backoff** -- automatic retry when tasks fail\n    16→6. **Dead letter queue** -- permanent storage for repeatedly-failing tasks\n    17→7. **Task dependencies** -- tasks that wait for other tasks to finish\n    18→8. **Concurrency control** -- limiting how many tasks run at once\n    19→9. **Progress and cancellation** -- tracking and aborting work\n    20→10. **Recurring tasks** -- cron-like scheduled task creation\n    21→11. **Middleware** -- intercepting and transforming tasks in a pipeline\n    22→12. **Graceful shutdown** -- orderly wind-down of the system\n    23→\n    24→Read `phases/*.md` for detailed requirements for each phase.\n    25→\n    26→## Getting Started\n    27→\n    28→- Export your main API from `src/index.ts`\n    29→- All implementation should live under `src/`\n    30→- No external runtime dependencies allowed (dev dependencies are pre-installed)\n    31→- Write your own tests as you go to verify your implementation\n    32→\n    33→## Validation\n    34→\n    35→```bash\n    36→npm run build   # TypeScript must compile\n    37→npm run lint    # No lint errors\n    38→```\n    39→\n    40→## Tips\n    41→\n    42→- Later phases will force you to rethink early decisions. Design with extensibility in mind.\n    43→- Tasks should have unique identifiers and track their lifecycle status.\n    44→- Consider how features like priorities, delays, and dependencies interact with each other.\n    45→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aee493ec-91df-4b3e-8021-5d8430142283","uuid":"d47886bb-6b65-487a-a040-7377d217922c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/TASK.md","content":"# Task Queue System\n\nBuild a fully-featured in-memory task queue system from scratch. The system should grow incrementally through 12 phases, each introducing new capabilities that build on the foundation laid by earlier phases.\n\n## Overview\n\nYour task queue should support adding tasks, processing them, and managing their lifecycle. Think of it like a simplified version of systems like Bull, BeeQueue, or Celery -- but entirely in-memory with no external dependencies.\n\nThe system evolves through 12 phases of increasing sophistication:\n\n1. **Basic queue** -- adding and processing tasks in order\n2. **Named queues** -- multiple independent queues\n3. **Priority** -- some tasks are more urgent than others\n4. **Delayed tasks** -- tasks that should wait before becoming available\n5. **Retry with backoff** -- automatic retry when tasks fail\n6. **Dead letter queue** -- permanent storage for repeatedly-failing tasks\n7. **Task dependencies** -- tasks that wait for other tasks to finish\n8. **Concurrency control** -- limiting how many tasks run at once\n9. **Progress and cancellation** -- tracking and aborting work\n10. **Recurring tasks** -- cron-like scheduled task creation\n11. **Middleware** -- intercepting and transforming tasks in a pipeline\n12. **Graceful shutdown** -- orderly wind-down of the system\n\nRead `phases/*.md` for detailed requirements for each phase.\n\n## Getting Started\n\n- Export your main API from `src/index.ts`\n- All implementation should live under `src/`\n- No external runtime dependencies allowed (dev dependencies are pre-installed)\n- Write your own tests as you go to verify your implementation\n\n## Validation\n\n```bash\nnpm run build   # TypeScript must compile\nnpm run lint    # No lint errors\n```\n\n## Tips\n\n- Later phases will force you to rethink early decisions. Design with extensibility in mind.\n- Tasks should have unique identifiers and track their lifecycle status.\n- Consider how features like priorities, delays, and dependencies interact with each other.\n","numLines":45,"startLine":1,"totalLines":45}}}
